1
00:00:07,405 --> 00:00:09,827
Greetings, I trust you had a fruitful day.

2
00:00:09,849 --> 00:00:12,332
I do not say happy, I say fruitful.

3
00:00:13,634 --> 00:00:29,716
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa

4
00:00:30,388 --> 00:00:46,695
It's not that I don't wish you had a happy day.

5
00:00:46,735 --> 00:00:54,027
It's just that happiness comes and goes, but we can make it fruitful through our spiritual practice.

6
00:00:54,289 --> 00:00:55,670
I just want to...

7
00:00:56,798 --> 00:01:02,686
A quote from one or two emails that came through concerning our subjects.

8
00:01:03,728 --> 00:01:07,593
Harold writes, I was on retreat last summer near Glastonbury.

9
00:01:07,612 --> 00:01:10,016
I was organised by Gaia House.

10
00:01:10,638 --> 00:01:14,944
And walking out in the evening, I discovered nearby was a cemetery.

11
00:01:15,625 --> 00:01:23,615
So a couple of evenings, I went and sat there and studied the gravestones, reflecting on how many had died before my current age, nearly 69.

12
00:01:24,996 --> 00:01:27,643
and how their bodies would now have rotted down to skeletons.

13
00:01:29,085 --> 00:01:34,597
However, I feel that experience was probably too comfortable to be really effective.

14
00:01:34,697 --> 00:01:44,760
That probably had to wait a meditation first thing in the morning, shortly after the first recommendation to socially distance, sorry, I'll start again,

15
00:01:45,043 --> 00:01:56,078
That probably had to wait a meditation first thing one morning shortly after the first recommendation to socially distance.

16
00:01:57,019 --> 00:02:04,469
When the potential impact of the events I had been attending up to then suddenly hit me with waves of panic.

17
00:02:04,972 --> 00:02:10,941
which no account of rationalization on actual probabilities of anything happening to me could come.

18
00:02:11,401 --> 00:02:18,371
So I just sat with it that morning and the next morning, and it slowly subsided, but not fun while it was happening.

19
00:02:18,971 --> 00:02:27,682
So that's when death strikes, when we feel the horror that we feel of serious sickness and death, you see.

20
00:02:28,824 --> 00:02:34,812
That horror, that sickness is the measure of this false idea of who I am, this self.

21
00:02:36,647 --> 00:02:43,057
He also then goes on to say that it was good to hear your reminiscences of frugality.

22
00:02:44,500 --> 00:02:55,757
I can remember about 1960 being tasked with cleaning the grate in my grandfather's house and carefully laying the fire for the evening with paper twists when my parents were staying there.

23
00:02:56,578 --> 00:03:02,486
When my parents bought their own house in the mid 60s, this had partial central heating.

24
00:03:02,921 --> 00:03:06,847
which heated the ground floor and their bedroom on the first floor, but not mine.

25
00:03:07,227 --> 00:03:08,909
Well, I wasn't there all the time.

26
00:03:09,430 --> 00:03:20,463
This meant in the winter, I would crawl out of bed and switch on the electric fan heater and then get back into bed until the room temperature was high enough for a morning wash to be considered.

27
00:03:21,786 --> 00:03:22,186
Softie.

28
00:03:23,949 --> 00:03:25,469
So there we are, a bit of frugality.

29
00:03:25,490 --> 00:03:31,478
I mean, these days, people wonder about in midwinter, in their shirts and blouses,

30
00:03:31,896 --> 00:03:37,903
with the house at, you know, 24, 26 degrees as if they were living on the Mediterranean.

31
00:03:39,185 --> 00:03:39,564
Terrible.

32
00:03:42,068 --> 00:03:46,592
I want to, oh yes, there's a little email here from May.

33
00:03:46,633 --> 00:03:53,600
And she spent time in Japan at Bukoku-ji, a training monastery there with her teacher.

34
00:03:54,020 --> 00:03:57,685
But there was a monk there from Chile called Chiku-san.

35
00:03:58,711 --> 00:04:02,574
He had traveled by foot alone in India and became ill with fever.

36
00:04:03,556 --> 00:04:08,320
He was in a village, it doesn't know where exactly, and had begun to accept that he would die.

37
00:04:08,382 --> 00:04:14,868
However, a herdsman brought him to his hut and treated him with what he believed was cow's urine.

38
00:04:15,649 --> 00:04:17,331
And he recovered after a week or so.

39
00:04:17,370 --> 00:04:19,132
There we are.

40
00:04:20,093 --> 00:04:23,697
It's meant to be fermented.

41
00:04:24,019 --> 00:04:28,043
So any germs or anything like that in it would hopefully be destroyed.

42
00:04:28,444 --> 00:04:32,928
But according to Ayurvedic medicine, it's Galmutra, that's what they call it.

43
00:04:33,528 --> 00:04:56,949
It contains nitrogen, sulfur, phosphate, sodium, manganese, iron, silicon, chlorine, magnesium, malic, citric and taric acids and calcium salts, vitamins A, B, C, B and E, minerals, lactose, enzymes, creatinine, hormones and gold acids, whatever that is.

44
00:04:57,216 --> 00:05:03,086
And it says that the Yoram is actually similar to the human body in some way.

45
00:05:03,105 --> 00:05:09,636
So an old Ayurvedic medicine, and it seems to have cured this Zen monk from Chile.

46
00:05:09,836 --> 00:05:10,516
So there we are.

47
00:05:12,740 --> 00:05:16,406
So those are just a little bit of replies.

48
00:05:16,966 --> 00:05:23,476
But I must say that yesterday evening, I didn't really stress enough that

49
00:05:23,795 --> 00:05:31,548
It's an occasion to begin, you know, to test our powers of renunciation and what happens when you renounce something.

50
00:05:32,468 --> 00:05:36,475
And for a, you know, for a Dharma teacher not to be teaching, that is terrible.

51
00:05:37,096 --> 00:05:41,043
And I gave myself very poor marks, but I'm going to make up for it now, you see.

52
00:05:41,704 --> 00:05:44,689
So remember that.

53
00:05:45,023 --> 00:05:48,146
The whole of the spiritual life could be said to be renunciation.

54
00:05:48,387 --> 00:05:51,310
And we're not talking about self-mortification.

55
00:05:51,331 --> 00:05:54,173
We're not talking about blaming and beating ourselves up.

56
00:05:54,555 --> 00:06:03,545
We're talking about seeing where desire, where we get caught up with desire, with reaction, wrong desire, of course.

57
00:06:05,007 --> 00:06:06,610
And this is just an opportunity.

58
00:06:06,629 --> 00:06:13,478
If we find ourselves, for instance, out of work, furloughed, or our wages reduced or whatever,

59
00:06:13,642 --> 00:06:17,346
It is an opportunity to, you know, to let go of certain things.

60
00:06:18,528 --> 00:06:21,050
Some of us may still be in job, but we can't fly anywhere.

61
00:06:21,091 --> 00:06:22,072
We can't go anywhere.

62
00:06:22,632 --> 00:06:26,297
We might be isolated, although I prefer the word secluded.

63
00:06:26,357 --> 00:06:32,783
And of course, we have to let go of certain desires that come up through our past habits.

64
00:06:33,665 --> 00:06:39,971
And it allows us to sort of sit with them, you know, sit with them and just feel their energy, feel their power.

65
00:06:40,853 --> 00:06:43,295
And the important thing is to

66
00:06:43,545 --> 00:06:46,529
stay, if you can, till the very end of that feeling.

67
00:06:47,130 --> 00:06:58,946
Because right at the end of that feeling, there's a switch, there's a change, there's a sense of being relieved, a sense of relief from that grip.

68
00:06:58,966 --> 00:07:00,687
The more the grip, the more the relief.

69
00:07:01,608 --> 00:07:04,291
And then you get that sense of peacefulness, you see.

70
00:07:04,793 --> 00:07:10,620
And remember that in that process, the energy is being transformed.

71
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:11,641
Nothing is lost.

72
00:07:12,403 --> 00:07:12,742
So

73
00:07:12,875 --> 00:07:24,492
whatever energy was caught up in that turbulence of desire, wrong desire, will then turn into pure energy, which can be used elsewhere.

74
00:07:24,951 --> 00:07:32,663
So given a given situation, it may manifest as love, compassion, joy, or just being peaceful, just being calm.

75
00:07:33,785 --> 00:07:37,329
So don't miss this opportunity.

76
00:07:37,370 --> 00:07:40,754
Every time you feel you want something, you know, really,

77
00:07:41,444 --> 00:07:46,752
you know, check it and stomp on it and say, ah, yes, this is a desire.

78
00:07:46,771 --> 00:07:47,552
Now let me have a look at it.

79
00:07:47,572 --> 00:07:48,415
Let me feel it.

80
00:07:50,478 --> 00:07:59,791
And then, you know, by renouncing those things that we have to renounce anyway, and this is the whole point, in a situation like this, you find yourself having to renounce stuff.

81
00:08:00,692 --> 00:08:09,526
So you may as well make spiritual capital from it, if you'll excuse the expression.

82
00:08:09,810 --> 00:08:12,475
Yes, and baths, giving up baths.

83
00:08:13,175 --> 00:08:14,798
Somebody's given up having hot baths.

84
00:08:15,137 --> 00:08:15,619
There we are.

85
00:08:18,502 --> 00:08:22,749
I mean, remember in the old days, medieval days, you only had one bath a year.

86
00:08:23,048 --> 00:08:25,211
Yes, it was taken in May or thereabouts.

87
00:08:25,793 --> 00:08:34,845
And you only had one big tub where, first of all, your dad got in and then your mum and then all the kids from the eldest to the youngest.

88
00:08:35,505 --> 00:08:35,986
And then...

89
00:08:36,153 --> 00:08:40,278
And that's where we get the phrase, you know, don't throw the baby out with the bathwater.

90
00:08:40,599 --> 00:08:45,585
So you know what the water must have looked like by the time they had their baths.

91
00:08:47,668 --> 00:08:53,816
Right up until I think it was the 80s, somewhere around about there, people were happy just having a shower a week, a bath a week.

92
00:08:53,836 --> 00:08:55,857
You know, now we find that very difficult.

93
00:08:55,918 --> 00:08:57,379
Now you have to have a shower every day.

94
00:08:57,841 --> 00:08:58,761
But actually, you don't.

95
00:08:59,001 --> 00:09:00,303
You don't need a shower every day.

96
00:09:02,342 --> 00:09:06,626
By the way, that's why most marriages took place in June.

97
00:09:07,027 --> 00:09:10,791
That was before, I suppose, people began to stink a little.

98
00:09:12,091 --> 00:09:18,357
So you can look at your lifestyle, yeah, and just see what's actually necessary.

99
00:09:18,558 --> 00:09:20,821
You know, what is actually necessary?

100
00:09:21,321 --> 00:09:23,864
And then you can add a little bit on top of that, maybe.

101
00:09:24,384 --> 00:09:28,467
But you're beginning to define what our indulgences are.

102
00:09:29,173 --> 00:09:38,067
It's funny how we need things just because we have them, but you don't need many things that we have.

103
00:09:38,086 --> 00:09:40,630
So I'm putting that aside now.

104
00:09:40,671 --> 00:09:53,950
And I am continuing to resolve to talk about the Eightfold Path and to answer the question as to, you know, to do that.

105
00:09:54,131 --> 00:09:58,547
But I do want to sidetrack a bit, and I've gone and left my boat.

106
00:09:58,707 --> 00:09:59,188
Oh, heavens.

107
00:09:59,750 --> 00:10:01,216
You have to excuse me just one second.

108
00:10:03,604 --> 00:10:04,648
One second.

109
00:10:39,491 --> 00:10:50,280
I just want to take a reading, really, that the Buddha began his teachings.

110
00:10:51,042 --> 00:11:04,432
There's a whole discourse here, the Arya Pariyasana Sutta, the discourse on the noble search, where the Buddha tells his life story, you might say, up until, or how he became fully liberated.

111
00:11:05,433 --> 00:11:08,756
And it gives you some idea of...

112
00:11:09,495 --> 00:11:12,198
the person, you know, how he was.

113
00:11:13,039 --> 00:11:21,169
So he said, when I was staying at Uruvela, as long as I chose, so that's where he became fully liberated.

114
00:11:21,230 --> 00:11:25,475
That's sort of close to what they think is present-day Bodh Gaya.

115
00:11:25,674 --> 00:11:27,317
Some of you will have been there.

116
00:11:28,018 --> 00:11:30,681
I set out to wander by stages to Benares.

117
00:11:31,722 --> 00:11:34,985
So that's present-day Varanasi on the Ganges there.

118
00:11:35,787 --> 00:11:38,811
Between Gaya, so that's the town near Bodh Gaya,

119
00:11:39,212 --> 00:11:44,399
And the place of enlightenment, the Ajivaka Upaka, saw me on the road.

120
00:11:44,698 --> 00:11:50,565
Now, the Ajivakas belonged to a sect that were fatalists, really.

121
00:11:51,306 --> 00:11:52,386
You could call them that.

122
00:11:52,528 --> 00:11:55,730
I've got it written down somewhere, if I can find it.

123
00:11:56,272 --> 00:11:57,312
Makali.

124
00:11:59,154 --> 00:12:00,596
I'm just trying to remember all these names.

125
00:12:00,736 --> 00:12:02,578
It's sort of, you know, it's terrible.

126
00:12:04,301 --> 00:12:06,503
Makali Gosala, who was a fatalist.

127
00:12:06,903 --> 00:12:08,325
Everything was predestined.

128
00:12:09,216 --> 00:12:18,405
There were many of these, remember, these people who'd gone out, mainly men, but some women, had left society to live as samanas.

129
00:12:18,986 --> 00:12:28,735
You know, the samana means somebody who strives for spiritual, or anybody who strives, but in this particular case, it's striving for spiritual attainment.

130
00:12:30,317 --> 00:12:36,303
Anyway, when Upaka sees him, he says, friend, your faculties are clear.

131
00:12:36,706 --> 00:12:39,168
The colour of your skin is pure and bright.

132
00:12:39,909 --> 00:12:41,451
Under whom have you gone forth?

133
00:12:42,113 --> 00:12:43,094
Who is your teacher?

134
00:12:43,695 --> 00:12:45,116
Whose dharma do you profess?

135
00:12:46,197 --> 00:12:58,273
And the Buddha replies in verses, I am the one who's transcended all and knower of all, unsullied among all things, renouncing all things by craving ceasing freed.

136
00:12:59,073 --> 00:13:02,899
Having known this for myself, to whom should I point as my teacher?

137
00:13:04,043 --> 00:13:13,153
I have no teacher and one like me exists nowhere in the world with all its gods because I have no person for my counterpart.

138
00:13:14,235 --> 00:13:15,937
I am the accomplished one in the world.

139
00:13:16,437 --> 00:13:17,860
I am the teacher supreme.

140
00:13:18,400 --> 00:13:23,306
I alone am a fully enlightened one whose fires are quenched and extinguished.

141
00:13:23,346 --> 00:13:25,408
That's the fires of greed, hatred and delusion.

142
00:13:26,370 --> 00:13:28,091
I go now to the city of Kazi.

143
00:13:28,592 --> 00:13:29,494
That's Varanasi.

144
00:13:29,861 --> 00:13:37,229
To set the motion, the wheel of the Dhamma, in a world that has become blind, I go to beat the drum of the deathless.

145
00:13:38,350 --> 00:13:39,932
That's very impressive, eh?

146
00:13:39,951 --> 00:13:47,500
But the Upaka replies, by your claims, friend, you ought to be the universal victor.

147
00:13:48,660 --> 00:13:53,806
The victors are those like me who have won to destruction of the saints.

148
00:13:54,125 --> 00:13:56,629
So remember, these are the four...

149
00:13:57,200 --> 00:14:00,082
basic problems that we have, basic misunderstandings.

150
00:14:00,943 --> 00:14:02,546
I have vanquished all evil states.

151
00:14:02,826 --> 00:14:04,869
Therefore, Upaka, I am a victor.

152
00:14:05,710 --> 00:14:11,475
Now, when this was said, the Ajivaka Upaka said, hmm, maybe so, friend.

153
00:14:12,177 --> 00:14:15,480
Shaking his head, he took a bypass and departed.

154
00:14:16,662 --> 00:14:21,386
So I think the Buddha realized this isn't quite the way he was going to spread the Dharma.

155
00:14:22,107 --> 00:14:25,591
Now, we also have to accept there's a bit of hagiography here.

156
00:14:25,631 --> 00:14:26,633
So hagiography is

157
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:28,462
the story of the saints.

158
00:14:29,823 --> 00:14:43,681
And you always build a saint up, you know, legends and myths all surround them and they become much greater in a sense in some ways than they actually were because of this mythology that surrounds them.

159
00:14:43,701 --> 00:14:47,525
So I doubt if he came out with a set of prepared verses.

160
00:14:48,366 --> 00:14:56,316
He probably said, you know, that he felt he was, that he knew himself to be fully liberated, but he didn't convince this Ajivaka.

161
00:14:56,802 --> 00:15:05,652
Now, that reminds me that when I was living at the Birmingham Buddhist Vihara in Birmingham, they used to come.

162
00:15:05,932 --> 00:15:10,317
There's been about the 80s, early, middle 80s, somewhere around about there.

163
00:15:10,736 --> 00:15:21,408
We used to get cards and letters from somebody announcing that the next world leader was living in London, somewhere in Pudding Street or something.

164
00:15:21,845 --> 00:15:28,993
And I remember picking these up, about seven or eight of them came to my memory, picking them up and thinking, oh, yeah, just like Ajivaka.

165
00:15:29,273 --> 00:15:30,414
Oh, yeah, right, okay.

166
00:15:30,554 --> 00:15:35,080
And I never got caught up to finding out who this person was.

167
00:15:36,822 --> 00:15:46,032
Anyway, he then, of course, is on his way, the Buddha's on his way, to see his old friends whom he'd been training with.

168
00:15:46,052 --> 00:15:46,873
And...

169
00:15:48,996 --> 00:15:50,259
Let me just read this through.

170
00:15:50,318 --> 00:15:56,807
So he wandered in stages and eventually came to Varanasi, Benares, to the deer park at Isipatana.

171
00:15:57,328 --> 00:15:59,010
And I approached the group of five.

172
00:15:59,071 --> 00:16:03,015
Now the bhikkhus saw me coming at a distance and they agreed amongst themselves.

173
00:16:03,476 --> 00:16:08,003
Friend, here comes the recluse Gautama who lives luxuriously.

174
00:16:08,143 --> 00:16:12,129
Remember he'd given up the path of self-mortification.

175
00:16:12,889 --> 00:16:15,813
Who gave up his striving and reverted to luxury.

176
00:16:16,469 --> 00:16:21,293
We should not pay homage to him or rise up for him or receive his bowl and outer robe.

177
00:16:22,154 --> 00:16:23,736
But a seat may be prepared for him.

178
00:16:23,996 --> 00:16:25,178
If he likes, he may sit down.

179
00:16:26,159 --> 00:16:32,125
However, as I approached those bhikkhus, they found themselves unable to keep their pact.

180
00:16:32,886 --> 00:16:38,913
One came to meet me, took my bowl and outer robe, another prepared a seat, and another set out water for my feet.

181
00:16:39,654 --> 00:16:41,736
However, they still addressed me as friend.

182
00:16:42,618 --> 00:16:43,759
Whereupon I told them,

183
00:16:44,092 --> 00:16:47,517
Do not address the Tathagata by the name of friend.

184
00:16:48,057 --> 00:16:50,580
Tathagata was how he referred to himself.

185
00:16:50,679 --> 00:16:52,902
It means the transcendent one.

186
00:16:55,365 --> 00:16:58,668
The Tathagata is the accomplished one, a fully enlightened one.

187
00:16:59,129 --> 00:17:01,971
Listen, Bhikkhus, the deathless has been attained.

188
00:17:02,493 --> 00:17:03,354
I shall instruct you.

189
00:17:03,413 --> 00:17:04,815
I shall teach you the Dharma.

190
00:17:05,375 --> 00:17:09,240
Practicing as you are instructed by realizing for yourself

191
00:17:09,794 --> 00:17:21,270
Here and now, through direct knowledge, you will soon enter into and abide in that supreme goal of the holy life, for the sake of which clansmen rightly go forth from home to homelessness.

192
00:17:21,711 --> 00:17:25,436
So that's a very pat phrase, okay, that you get throughout the scriptures.

193
00:17:29,942 --> 00:17:33,468
And then he tries to talk to them, of course, about this.

194
00:17:34,169 --> 00:17:38,855
And then there's this lovely passage here.

195
00:17:39,442 --> 00:17:50,575
where four or five, the usual thing is everybody tries three times, you see, or a second time, and then he actually says the same thing a third time.

196
00:17:51,174 --> 00:17:58,462
And then he asks them, he says, Bikku's, Bikku, remember, is anybody's list, but here it's his five friends.

197
00:17:59,183 --> 00:18:01,306
Have you ever heard me speak like this before?

198
00:18:02,207 --> 00:18:03,508
They said, no, Venerable Sir.

199
00:18:03,989 --> 00:18:07,813
He says, the target is the accomplished one, and then he goes through this business.

200
00:18:08,198 --> 00:18:12,083
And then he says, I was able to convince the bhikkhus of the group of five.

201
00:18:12,884 --> 00:18:17,828
Then I sometimes instructed two bhikkhus while the other three went for alms.

202
00:18:18,609 --> 00:18:23,715
And the six of us lived on what the other three bhikkhus brought back from their alms round.

203
00:18:23,736 --> 00:18:27,279
Sometimes I instructed three bhikkhus while the other two went on alms.

204
00:18:27,780 --> 00:18:32,046
And the six of us lived on what those two bhikkhus brought back from their alms round.

205
00:18:32,701 --> 00:18:54,760
Then the Bhikkhus of five, thus taught and instructed by me, being themselves subject to birth, having understood the danger in what is subject to birth, seeking the unborn supreme security from bondage, Nibbana, attained the unborn supreme security from bondage, Nibbana.

206
00:18:55,521 --> 00:19:00,125
Being themselves subject to aging, sickness, death, sorrow and defilement,

207
00:19:00,528 --> 00:19:30,130
having understood the danger in what is subject to aging, sickness, death, sorrow, and defilement, seeking the unaging, unailing, deathless, sorrowless, and undefiled supreme security from bondage, nibbana, they attained the unaging, unailing, deathless, sorrowless, undefiled supreme security from bondage, nibbana.

208
00:19:30,413 --> 00:19:33,096
The knowledge and vision arose in them.

209
00:19:33,655 --> 00:19:35,719
Our deliverance is unshakable.

210
00:19:36,239 --> 00:19:37,520
This is our last birth.

211
00:19:37,901 --> 00:19:40,063
There is no renewal of becoming.

212
00:19:40,923 --> 00:19:47,912
So there you have a nice little passage which gives us some idea of his early movements.

213
00:19:48,913 --> 00:19:52,957
But of course, they've been sort of souped up a bit with verses and stuff like that.

214
00:19:53,377 --> 00:19:57,602
But at least we can sort of get an image of him, of how he

215
00:19:57,952 --> 00:20:20,103
he walked, I think it's about 500 miles, I've got it somewhere, 250 miles, he walked 250 miles from Bodh Gaya to Sarnath, with the sole purpose of seeking out these old companions whom he felt were open enough or developed enough to receive his Dharma.

216
00:20:21,865 --> 00:20:22,746
So,

217
00:20:25,138 --> 00:20:45,380
Time is passing on and I did want to read the actual discourse, which is what you might call the root discourse of Theravada, the root discourse of Buddhism, frankly.

218
00:20:45,641 --> 00:20:49,223
It's not just Theravada, it's the root discourse and it's all about the Four Noble Truths.

219
00:20:49,944 --> 00:20:54,690
So I'm afraid because time moves on, I shall have to leave that little delight

220
00:20:54,940 --> 00:20:55,904
for tomorrow evening.

221
00:20:57,151 --> 00:21:00,428
And I will be getting round to the Eightfold Path sooner.

